question:
Suppose that $$A=\left( 
 \begin{array}{rrr}
1 & 2  & -1  \\ 
0 & 0 & 2  \\ 
-1 & -2 & 3  \\ 
2 & 4 & 0 \end{array}
\right)$$ and $$B=\left( 
 \begin{array}{rrr}
0 & 1  & 1  \\ 
2 & 2 & 0  \\ 
0 & 3 & 2 \end{array}
\right).$$ Which of the following matrices has rank $3$?

answer1:
$\begin{cases}
x(t) = c_1e^{t}-\frac{c_2}{3}e^{-2t} \\
y(t) = c_2e^{-2t}
\end{cases}$, where $c_1, c_2 \in \mathbb{R}$.

answer2:
$\begin{cases}
x(t) = c_1e^{t}-\frac{c_2}{3}e^{-2t} \\
y(t) = c_1e^{t}+c_2e^{-2t}
\end{cases}$, where $c_1, c_2 \in \mathbb{R}$.

answer3:
$\begin{cases}
x(t) = c_1e^{t}-\frac{c_2}{3}e^{-3t} \\
y(t) = c_2e^{-2t}
\end{cases}$, where $c_1, c_2 \in \mathbb{R}$.

answer4:
$\begin{cases}
x(t) = c_1e^{-t}-\frac{c_2}{3}e^{2t} \\
y(t) = c_2e^{2t}
\end{cases}$, where $c_1, c_2 \in \mathbb{R}$.

